---------------------------------------------------------
🧠 1. What “Concurrent Users” Means
---------------------------------------------------------
Concurrent users = people using the site *at the same time*.
It does not mean total users for the day.

Example:
If 50 people click “Log In” at the same second, that’s 50 concurrent users.
If 300 people visit over 10 minutes, concurrency is much lower.

---------------------------------------------------------
⚙️ 2. Performance by Activity Type
---------------------------------------------------------

| Activity Type                | Concurrent Users Supported | Expected Result                |
|------------------------------|-----------------------------|--------------------------------|
| **Login Requests**           | 50–70 at once               | Smooth (0.2–0.6 sec response)  |
| **Active Browsing**          | 150–200 at once             | Stable, minor delay possible   |
| **Open SocketIO Connections**| 80–130                      | Lag starts, higher latency     |
| **250+ SocketIO Connections**| >200                        | Unstable, timeouts likely      |

---------------------------------------------------------
⚡ 3. Class Scenario (250–300 Students)
---------------------------------------------------------
If 250–300 students use the site *within 2 minutes*:

✅ Logins → Fine. Requests will spread out, average load is small.
✅ Browsing → Fine. Static pages and simple requests are lightweight.
⚠️ Real-time SocketIO (chat/live updates) → Heavy. Expect lag or disconnections if everyone connects at once.

Render’s instance cannot hold 250–300 persistent sockets because of
limited RAM (512 MB) and shared CPU power. Max students is roughly 80-100

---------------------------------------------------------
🔧 4. Recommended Practices
---------------------------------------------------------
1. Ask students to log in gradually (over 1–2 minutes).
2. Open SocketIO connections only when necessary.
3. Add short random delay before connecting (1–5 seconds).
4. Keep pages lightweight; avoid large image uploads.
5. Use caching or external storage for heavy content (e.g., S3).

---------------------------------------------------------
🚀 5. Summary Verdict
---------------------------------------------------------
✅ Logins & normal browsing for 250–500 students — **WORKS FINE**.
⚠️ Full real-time chat or dashboard for everyone at once — **NOT RECOMMENDED** on free tier.
🔼 Upgrade or stagger connections for smoother experience.

---------------------------------------------------------
📊 Estimated Capacity
---------------------------------------------------------
- ~50–70 simultaneous logins
- ~150–200 active browsers
- ~80–120 live SocketIO connections
- 10,000–50,000 total users per day (spread out)

---------------------------------------------------------
🧩 Key Takeaway
---------------------------------------------------------
Your current Render setup is well-optimized for a class environment
as long as everyone doesn’t open real-time connections (SocketIO) at the same moment.

“Login and browse – yes ✅
All students chatting live – no ⚠️”

